column3: Most Notable Character/Deed
column5: Description

column3: Epic of Gilgamesh
column5: Gilgamesh was a legendary hero king of Uruk, a Sumerian city-state that existed around 2000 BC. The record of his life and exploits can be found in the Epic of Gilgamesh poem, which is one of the oldest records that still exist. If the poem is to be believed, he is a demigod offspring from Lugalbanda and Ninsun, the Goddess of wild cows. With the strength that can match mythical creatures.

column3: England conquest
column5: William the Bastard, William the Duke of Normandy, William the Conqueror, was the first Norman to rule over England after wrestling the control from the Anglo-Saxon king, Harold Godwinson, in the invasion of England in 1066. From the still-young House of Normandy, which ruled over the Normandy region since 911, William's rule was always full of conflicts since childhood and fought his first battle at the age of 20 years old. William was one of the prime contenders whom King Edward the Confessor appointed as his heir. The throne of England is always in his destiny, and nothing will stop his rightful conquest.

column3: Castles construction near Wales
column5: William fitzOsbern was a cousin and close companion of William the Conqueror. He was a nobleman who ruled over Breteuil, Normandy, before becoming Earl of Hereford and Essex after the Norman conquest. After the invasion, he remained one of the most important political figures in Norman England, while his name became and is still renowned for many castles that he commissioned around the Welsh border. He met his end in the Battle of Cassel while pursuing the wealth of Flanders principality.

column3: Responsible for Godwinson’s exile from England
column5: Eustace II (Nickname Eustace with moustaches) was a Count of Boulogne who was excommunicated for marrying his close relative. Eustace was the one that caused the rebellion and exile of House Godwinson from a brawl with the people of Dovers. He led the charge of Norman Knights and was struck by a battle-axe from Saxon Huscarl in the Battle of Hastings. After the invasion, Eustace rebelled against William the Conqueror due to the dissatisfaction of war spoil and possibly for a claim on the English throne. The rebellion ultimately failed, but William and Eustace reconciled with Eustace retaining some of his holdings and remaining in William's court.

column3: Exiled twice with his wife for their too audacious ruling
column5: William of Evreux was a Norman nobleman who fought alongside William the Conqueror in the Battle of Hastings and contributed to the construction of the Norman fleet. Not much is known of his role in the battle, but after the invasion, William was granted multiple landholdings but no noteworthy nobility title from the war contribution. Later on in his life, William married Hervise of Nevers, daughter of William the Conqueror, inherited Count of Evreux from his father, and participated in many great battles, like the Battle of Tinchebray under King Henry I. As he died childlessly, all of his possessions were seized by Henry I to prevent foreign inheritance by his French relative.

column3: The first Earl of Leicester
column5: Robert of Beaumont was a Norman nobleman who fought in the Battle of Hastings on the side of William the Conqueror. Robert was highly praised in the chronicle for being a wise learned man. An advisor to three Norman Kings, starting from William the Conqueror, William's son William Rufus, and then King Henry. It is believed that Robert fought with the French (Frank) troops on the right wing of the Norman army. He later became the Count of Meulan and Earl of Leicester. He was the last living Norman noble that fought in the Battle of Hastings to die in 1118 AD. The story is that he died of shame for having the woman he fancied stolen by another nobleman.

column3: Handsome and brave with a strong religious belief
column5: Geoffrey II was the Count of Mortagne and later Count of Perche, who participated in the Norman invasion and Battle of Hastings on William's side. After the invasion, he fought against Robert of Belleme, a prominent noble, in a land dispute but ultimately failed. Later on, he became renowned for his spiritual pursuit and charitable acts, such as establishing leper colonies, the places to keep lepers isolated from society in his region.

column3: Veteran crusader of many battles
column5: Walter Giffard was one of the closest companions of William the Conqueror, who fought with him long before the Norman invasion. A veteran knight, landowner, and later Baron of Long Crendon, Walter Giffard fought in the Reconquista against the Moors and contributed to the Norman invasion significantly and personally fought in the Battle of Hastings. The first warhorse that William the Conqueror rode in the Battle of Hastings was a gift from Walter, who received it as a reward from the Spanish king for his accomplishment during the Reconquista.

column3: Commander of Normandy duchy’s army
column5: Hugh II of Montfort was a Norman nobleman from Montfort-sur-Risle who fought alongside William the Conqueror long before the invasion and likely participated in the Battle of Hastings. Although his role in the Battle of Hastings is not evidently recorded, the numerous reward of holding from Domesday book evidence suggests that his contribution to the battle are likely to be significant. Hugh was appointed as the justice administrator for the Kingdom under Odo of Bayeux and William FitzOsbern and the governor of the Castle of Dover, Odo's main fortress. The castle was attacked by Eustace II during his absence in 1067 AD.

column3: Declined standard-bearer role to fight near Duke William
column5: A Norman nobleman from the infamous House of Tosny created by his grandfather, Raoul I of Tosny, "The Moor Eater", who literally ate the boiled Moorish prisoners of war. Raoul II of Tosny, fought on the side of William the Conqueror in the Battle of Mortimer. Later he also participated in the Battle of Hastings, possibly fighting nearby the Duke himself. After the invasion, he was rewarded greatly by King William with lands and war spoils. However, his life had no shortage of conflicts. He fought against William of Evreux and later on against Robert of Beaumont.

column3: Banished by paranoid Duke William but reconciled later
column5: Hugh of Grandmesnil was one of the noble companions of William the Conqueror that originally got banished by William from Normandy but managed to regain the Duke's Favour again years later. He joined the Duke in Norman conquest and personally fought in multiple battles. He was rewarded handsomely with multiple landholdings and was appointed the Sheriff of Leicestershire. He remained an important political figure during William's reign and joined in a conflict against Robert of Beaumont.

column3: Create the first Cluniac priory in England
column5: William of Warenne was among Norman nobles that participate in Council of Lillebonne and Norman invasion. After the successful invasion, he received numerous landholdings as a reward but remained somewhat minor noble in Norman court. Only later, He became Earl of Surrey during the reign of William the Conqueror's third son, William II Rufus (The Red) for his loyalty to the king during the rebellion. He fought against the rebels and met his end during the Siege of Pevensey Castle.

column3: Lost against the Danish invasion and became hostage
column5: William Malet was a minor noble and a key officer in William the Conqueror's army during the Battle of Hastings. Although there is a record to support that he fought in the battle, it is not known of his exact role nor contribution in the invasion. Nevertheless, there is a record that the Duke gave Harold Godwinson's corpse to him for burial instead of accepting Harold's mother's gold offers and he was significantly rewarded with lands and wealth for his contribution to the invasion and became Sheriff of Yorkshire.

column3: Commissioner of the Bayeux Tepastry
column5: Another half-brother of William the Conqueror and older brother of Robert of Mortain. Odo of Bayeux was a cleric turned warrior and Earl of Kent renown for his contribution to the Norman invasion. He was also very likely the person who commissioned Bayeux Tapestry, an immensely important historical relic of propagandistic nature that chronicle the events leading up to the Battle of Hastings. Interestingly his life after the invasion was not a pleasant one. After multiple imprisonments and a failed rebellion, he died on his journey for the First Crusade in Sicily.

column3: Papal standard-bearer during the invasion of England
column5: Turstin FitzRolf is the name of a person who was a companion of William the Conqueror. With an unknown role and accomplishment, he was more likely a knight under William's service than a minor noble. He was chosen as the Papal standard bearer during the Battle of Hastings after Raoul II of Tosny and Walter Giffard rejected Duke William's offer for the role. After the invasion, he was granted multiple Baronies and holdings in Somerset. No tale remains of his deed after the invasion, nor his family line, most of the lands that he held seem to be passed on to other families for an unknown reason after his death.

column3: Fell from power but found redemption in spiritual
column5: Geoffrey of Montbray was a Bishop from a noble house and a political advisor for William the Conqueror, likely both before and after the invasion. Geoffrey of Montbray was a charismatic speaker and acquaintance with many prominent figures like Pope Leo IX and the infamous Norman adventurer Robert Guiscard. He fought in the Battle of Hastings and participated in multiple battles against the subsequent rebellions. As a religious cleric, the chronicle remarks that Geoffrey was more skilled in the military matter than his official duty.

column3: Skilful but short-tempered, wife beater
column5: Robert of Mortain was a Count of Mortain and William the Conqueror's another half-brother who is no doubt one of the closest companions of Duke William. His name is recorded as a participant in the war council and contributor to the invasion fleet. Not much is known for his role in the battle but after the invasion, Robert was rewarded a significant portion of war spoil and land for his contribution. He was also the leader of the failed revolt against William II over the succession dispute.

column3: Favourite logistic supervisor of Odo of Bayeux
column5: Wadard is the name of the person that appear in Bayeux Tapestry and Domesday book who believed to be a nobleman of unknown origin. It was believed that he may be a noble from Bayeux or less possibly a residence near Hastings. Regardless of origin, it is crucial that his name appear in the Tapestry, which indicate his importance to William's court and likely fought in the Battle of Hastings.

column3: Favourite scout platoon leader of Odo of Bayeux
column5: Vital is the name of another person beside Wadard that appear in Bayeux Tapestry. It is believed that he was one of Odo of Bayeux's followers and tenants beside Wadard and the dwarf, Turold. He very likely fought in the Battle of Hastings but not much else is known about his origin, accomplishment and fate after the invasion.

column3: Returned to Normandy after the invasion
column5: Gilbert of Auffay was one of the Norman nobles who followed William the Conqueror to invade England and participated in the Battle of Hastings. Not much is known about him and his family except that they are from a century-old noble house in Saint-Valery, Northern Normandy. After the invasion, he declined William's offer of lands in England and returned to his holding in Saint-Valery and ruled there until his final rest.

column3: The first of Bohun House
column5: Humphrey I of Bohun, "The Bearded" or "The Old", was a Norman noble and the first known Bohun house, which continued to exist for at least two centuries after his death. He was also William the Conqueror's godfather and accompanied William in the invasion and participated in the Battle of Hastings. He was rewarded generously for his contribution to the invasion and remained a prominent figure in William's rule. Humphrey became the Baron of Taterford with the noblest title "Champion and Defender of the Throne".

column3: Killed while chasing fleeing Saxons
column5: Engenulf of Laigle, or Engenulphe of Laigle, was a Baron of Laigle who accompanied William the Conqueror in the invasion. He was part of the Laigel family who ruled over the town of L'Aigle since the rule of Duke Richard II of Normandy. Not much else is known about Engenulf's accomplishment or history except that he accompanied William of Normandy to invade England in 1066 AD. He was the only confirmed named companion that fought on William's side to die in the Battle of Hastings. Ironically, his death proves that chasing after an already fleeing enemy force does not always guarantee a risk-free kill.

column3: Powerful but lost everything in a failed civil war
column5: Richard fitz Gilbert was a Norman noble and another half-brother of William the Conqueror. As Richard was an illegitimate son of Gilbert, Count of Brionne, he did not inherit the title when his father died. Richard accompanied William the Conqueror in the Invasion of England and was well rewarded with a vast amount of English lands including the lordship of Clare, in Suffolk. Richard was also part of the succession rebellion in 1088. He was punished severely after the failed rebellion.

column3: Talented fighter and entertainer, possibly fictional
column5: Taillefer was the name of the jongleur or clown that led the Norman army into battle during the Battle of Hastings, according to various Norman chronicles. He sang the Song of Roland and juggled his sword while the troops walked behind him. Some chronicles also mentioned that he managed to cut down several Saxon challengers and rushed into the enemy line while singing.

column3: Might or might not fight in the Battle of Hastings
column5: Father of William of Evreux, Richard was Count of Évreux who possibly participated in the Battle of Hastings at around the age of 50. Robert and his son were presented during the War Council at Lillebonne that convened on the invasion. The matter of his being at the battle itself is still that of debating topic among scholars as he died of old age the year after.

column3: Pretty much the Lord (Sheriff) of Devon
column5: Baldwin FitzGilbert, or Baldwin the Sheriff, was one of the wealthy and influential Norman noblemen during the time of William the Conqueror's reign. He and his older brother, Richard FitzGilbert, fought in the Battle of Hastings and also participated in the following series of sieges against the remaining Saxon lords that resisted William's rule after the battle. Baldwin was rewarded with the largest number of manors in Devon and was titled Sheriff of Devon.

column3: Brother inherited his wealth as he died with no son
column5: The eldest brother of the Harcourt family that participated in the Battle of Hastings along with his younger brothers. Errand of Harcourt was a man of little renown, as suspiciously described by Auguste Le Prévost. He possibly commanded a company of Norman archers during the battle and was remembered as riding a very swift horse to aid William of Normandy all he could. He was rewarded with land in Leicestershire after the battle.

The younger brother of Errand of Harcourt, Robert "The Strong" of Harcourt, also probably fought in the Battle of Hastings alongside his brothers. Unlike his older brother, Robert returned to Normandy after the battle and returned to rule the family land in Harcourt. He later became the head of the Harcourt family and built the Castle of Harcourt. Robert also participated in the civil war against Waleran of Beaumont and was rewarded with lands in England which his sons inherited later.

A member of the Crispin noble family from Normandy and a younger brother of William Crispin, both vassals of Duke William of Normandy. Gilbert II was already a noble with holdings in Tillières and followed his lord to invade England in 1066 AD.

A member of the Crispin noble family from Normandy and a long-time vassal of William of Normandy since his ascension as duke. William I Crispin, with his two younger brothers, Gilbert and Milo, were likely to be presented at the Battle of Hastings. All three Crispin brothers were rewarded with lands in England after the battle.

The eldest child of the Ferrers house, Henry of Ferrers, was a Norman noble who participated in the Battle of Hastings on the side of Duke William of Normandy, where only one sibling survived the combat. Henry, for his accomplishment, was rewarded with two hundred of manors throughout England and Wales. He later became an royal administrator in charge of the Domesday survey and the Domesday book record.

Likely the most powerful man in Normandy and a close advisor of Duke William since the start of his reign. Roger de Beaumont was the lord of Beaumont-le-Roger who was loyal to the young Duke, unlike many others who revolted during the ascension. He was the leading figure in guiding William to crush the pretenders and govern the country. Although he was presented during the war councils to invade England, he might not participate in the Battle of Hastings due to old age and likely remained at the main camp.

Roger (Rogier) of Montgomery the Great, a very powerful Norman nobleman and a distant cousin of William of Normandy. Roger was a close associate of William and served as his advisor in the time of war. It is not conclusive whether this man joined William in the invasion of Normandy or not, but if he did, then it is recorded that he was one of the commanders for the right wing of the army. Roger was rewarded with almost the entirety of West Sussex and many other regions after the invasion and became one of the most powerful noblemen in England.

A member of the relatively poor Norman noble prior to the invasion of England, Roger Bigod was a household knight of William of Normandy. Described as having a small body but brave and bold, Roger and his father, Robert, were rewarded with numerous lands and manors in East England, so it is likely that he was a favourite of the Duke long before the invasion. With a stroke of luck, Roger became influential in the English royal court. He fought against the Danish raider alongside William Malet and Ralph of Gael and joined the rebel in the civil war against William II, for which he was pardoned after the defeat.

A Norman noble of Germanic heritage who participated in the Battle of Hastings, his deed of "slew many English" were the only record left of him for his part in the battle. Richard of Courcy was given a reward of titles and holdings in Somerset and other South West regions in England for the accomplishment. A scoundrel who stole from the Abbey of Sainte-Trinité and served both the sons of William the Conqueror during the civil war.

column3: Gallant, bloody, and merciless noble warrior
column5: William of Molins (later Molyneux) was a Norman nobleman from Rouen, Normandy. It is believed and claimed by his family that this William fought in the Battle of Hastings and was rewarded with lands in Lancashire. Described as a gallant soldier for his deed at Hastings and also a bloody slaughterer that killed everyone with no mercy. A soldier's life full of battles, William of Molins managed to live to old age and died at his own castle.

Fulk of Aulney or Fulco Basset was possibly one of the companions who fought against the Saxons in the William of Normandy army during the Battle of Hastings. A Norman nobleman of unknown history, the Aulney family was relatively well-known from Burgundy. Fulk probably died before the Domesday book, as only his descendants were found in the record.

column3: One of the few known Norman noble died at Hastings
column5: Another named noble who might fight in the Battle of Hastings and fell in combat. Nothing else is known of him.

column3: Revolted but later became loyal to William of Normandy
column5: Niel II (also III) of Saint-Sauveur, or Nigel of Cotentin, was among the Norman nobles who revolted against the ascension of William of Normandy. He fought in the Battle of Val-ès-Dunes under Guy of Burgundy. After he survived the battle, Niel became a vassal of William again and might join in the invasion of England. The only existing record of his deeds in the Battle of Hastings compliments his bravery in charging into the English line and saving many nobles from their predicament.

column3: Faith didn’t save him from falling from his pious work
column5: Walter of Lacy (or Lassy) was a Norman noble who fought in the Battle of Hastings, along with another of Lacy, Ilbert. It is not known what the relationship is between the two of Lacy, one possibility is that they are siblings. After the invasion, he was rewarded with holdings in England. Walter remained a prominent noble in England, he and William Fitz Osbern led an army to subdue the revolts led by the Princes of Wales. Walter died in an accident during the construction of the Church of St. Peter that he commissioned where he slipped and fell from a ladder during the inspection.

Ilbert of Lacy (or Lassy) was a Norman noble who fought in the Battle of Hastings. The possibility existed that he may be the same person as Walter of Lacy, though if not he and Walter were among a group of knights who charged into the English line fearlessly.

A member of the Vassy family. This Norman nobleman with the name Robert, together with Ivo, joined William of Normandy in the invasion of England and fought in the Battle of Hastings. No record can be found of what relationship between these two, but we know that Robert was rewarded with several baronies in Northampton, Warwick, Lincoln and Leicester.

Another member of the Vassy family joined William of Normandy in the invasion of England and fought in the Battle of Hastings. Ivo of Vassy was a man of a very little history, and we only know that he was rewarded with the marriage with Alda, the granddaughter of Gilbert Tison, who was a noble from Alnwick, where Ivo later became the ruler. The Alnwick Castle that still stands today was commissioned by Ivo.

Norman noble from the infamous family of Marmion, referred to as "Old Roger (Robert) Marmion" by Wace, the Norman chronicler who participated in the Battle of Hastings and was rewarded the tower of Tamworth, the very same tower as sung in the poem of Marmion by Walter Scott. Which would make him the first of Marmion to rule Tamworth town.

A close companion of William of Normandy, William Patrie of La Lande, was presented during the campaign against Brittany, the oath of vassal from Harold Godwinson to the Duke, and the invasion of England. During the Battle of Hastings, legend says that this man proclaim to the English army that he would personally slay Harold for betraying the oath. For his deeds at the battle, William Patrie was awarded with lands and baronies in Norfolk and Suffolk.

William Avenel of Biarz was a seneschal of Robert of Mortain who participated in the Battle of Hastings. It is possible that five of his brothers also participated in the battle, but no evidence existed to confirm such speculation.

Robert of Oyly was a powerful and stern Norman nobleman, he was among those who followed William of Normandy to invade England and fought in the Battle of Hastings. For his feat in battle, he became High Sheriff of Oxfordshire, who owned much of the lands there. Many building projects were commissioned by Robert, including the still-standing Oxford Castle. Many praise him for his pious contribution to building projects for the churches.

A Norman nobleman who is a close associate with Robert of Oyly, presumably to be his sworn brother-in-arms. Jean of Ivri was a vassal of William of Normandy and likely participated in the invasion of England. It is unknown what spoils of war he received after the invasion from William the Conqueror, but there is a record that he received some holdings from Robert, including the honour of Saint Valeries.

A member of a powerful Norman baronial family, William Painel was among those who fought in the Battle of Hastings. It is recorded that he, along with Avenel of Biarz and Robert Bertram the Crooked, fought valiantly together and killed many Englishmen that day. William remained in Normandy after the conquest and was rewarded with lands in Cotentin.

Robert Bertram le Tort the Crooked rode alongside William Painel and Avenel of Biarz during the Battle of Hastings. Described as strong on horseback and slew many Englishmen that day. Robert was a Norman nobleman from Briquebec, Normandy, and a descendant of the infamous Anslech de Bricquebec, who was one of the founders of Normandy.

One of the knight brothers who participated in the Battle of Hastings, William of Say, was a Norman noble from Sai, Orne. His exact contribution to the battle was not recorded but was likely to be significant enough that Robert Wace recorded his name among those who were presented at the battle.

One of the knight brothers who participated in the Battle of Hastings, Robert (or Picot) of Say, was a Norman noble who was rewarded with lands in Shropshire after the invasion and served as the vassal of Roger of Montgomery. He also participated in the fight against the rebelling Saxon lords and seized the Clun Castle from Eadric the Wild.

Hugh of Port was another Norman noble who followed William of Normandy to invade England. He originated from Port-en-Bessin, the land which he left after the invasion success. Hugh became the first sheriff of Kent and later lord of Basing. A likely shrewd and charming man as he managed to secure more than 50 holdings in Hampshire and nearby areas.

William Peverel the Elder was one of the most influential Norman nobles during the rule of William of Normandy. Clearly a favourite of the conqueror as he was rewarded with more than a hundred manors and land holdings around Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire as a reward after the Battle of Hastings. The Honour of Peverel, which is the area in England with surrounding castles, was derived from his holdings and name.

The younger brother of Henry of Ferrers, who also fought in the Battle of Hastings, although, unlike his elder brother, William was unfortunate enough to be one of the few named nobles on the Norman side who lost their lives in the battle.
Killed during the Battle of Val-ès-Dunes

column3: One of the richest persons in Medieval history
column5: Alan Rufus (Alain Fergant), or "the Red (beard)", was a Breton nobleman and close companion of William the Conqueror. As part of the Invasion of England, he is the commander of the Breton forces in William's army. After the successful invasion, Alan was granted amass fortune and the title Earl of Richemont and remained an important figure in William's court and ruling achievement, which later on allowed him to become one of the wealthiest individuals in Europe.

column3: The last rebel against William of Normandy in England
column5: This was an English and Breton-born noble who led the last revolt of the earls against William of Normandy, the very last resistant of remaining Saxon lords against the encroaching grasp of Norman power in England. Ralph (Radulf) of Gael was a former ally of William and was likely to fight in the Battle of Hastings on the side of the Norman. Brave and confident, his resistant to William's rule lasted until the death of William himself.

A French nobleman who allied with William of Normandy during the invasion of England. Hamo of Crevecceur, along with those from Driencourt and Briencort, followed the duke into the Battle of Hastings. Not much else is known of this man.

A French noble from Flanders who fought on the side of William of Normandy, Drogo of Brevere (Beuvrière), was of valour and bravery. He was rewarded with numerous lands in Easter and Northern England, including the Isle of Holderness, where he commissioned Skipsea Castle. With deceit unmatched his bravery. He killed his own wife (unknown whether accidentally or intentionally) and tried to hide the deed by requesting King William for funding to travel with his wife to Flanders for escape. William later discovered the plot and ordered the arrest of Drogo, who already escaped long before.

Aimery (or Aimeri, Aumari, Haimon) IV of Thouars was a Viscount who fought against William the Conqueror in the Siege of Ambrieres. During the Norman invasion, he joined the Norman force and commanded the Breton wing of the army during the Battle of Hastings. After the invasion, he returned to his holding in France and ruled there for another three decades until he was assassinated.

Gerbod the Fleming was a Frankish noble (tenants-in-chief) from Flanders. He participated in the Battle of Hastings and was rewarded the Earl of Chester title. However, the man had no shortage of misfortune. He lost a portion of his holdings due to a series of political events in the same year and the Earl title after he was captured by his enemies in the Battle of Cassel in Flanders. His fate became uncertain afterwards, some said he escaped from captivity and became a monk, while others said he died a prisoner.

Odo or Eudes was Count of Champagne, Troyes, Meaux, and Aumale. Born around 1040 from Etienne II and Adele. He inherited the Countdom of Troyes and Meaux from his father at a young age. He is a nephew of Duke Robert, the father of William the Conqueror. He also married the sister of the Conqueror, Adelaide. Such marriage should be prohibited by the Catholic Church but nevertheless lasted until his death. This Odo also accompanied his brother-in-law to England but was not rewarded with lands in England. He concocted a plot to install his son, Stephen, as a King of England and failed miserably.

column3: The last Saxon king of England
column5: The Saxon king of England, Harold Godwinson is the rightful heir of Edward the Confessor (at least according to himself). Originally the Earl of East Anglia, Harold was already extremely influential person long before his kingship. His short reign of one year as the last Saxon king was nothing short of troubling, having to defend against both invasions from Norse and Norman in the same year. He and his two brothers were killed in the Battle of Hastings thus signal the new reign of Norman in Albion.

column3: Failed to persuade Harold against engaging Normans
column5: Gyrth Godwinson was the younger brother of Harold Godwinson, King of England. Godwinson was one of the most powerful houses during the reign of Edward the Confessor, Gyrth himself hold multiple Earldom in East England along with his brothers. Along with his brothers, Gyrth commanded a significant portion of the Saxon army in the Battle of Hastings. It is believed that Gyrth is killed by William the Conqueror himself in personal combat as recorded in multiple sources.

Leofwine Godwinson was the younger of Harold Godwinson and Earl of multiple regions in East England. Having followed Harold throughout his life, it is interesting to note that Leofwine and the other brother did not fight in the Battle of Stamford Bridge. Nevertheless, Leofwine along with his two brothers fought and perished in the Battle of Hastings.

column3: One of few known Saxon nobles that died at Hastings
column5: Godric was a Saxon sheriff of Berkshire who fought in the Battle of Hastings on the side of Harold Godwinson's army. Not much is known about Godric beside his land ownership and title from the Domesday Book. But according to the chronicle of the monastery of Abingdon, he was part of a few named individuals killed during the battle.

column3: One of few known Saxon nobles that died at Hastings
column5: Thurkill was one of the landowners or thanes who participated in the Battle of Hastings on Harold Godwinson's side. Most of the thanes were the leader of the Fyrd militias, while the noble led alongside the Huscarls. Thurkill, along with many other unnamed thanes and nobles, perished in the battle along with their kings. Thus, leaving a vast amount of land to be claimed as war spoil by William the Conqueror.

column3: One of few known Saxon nobles that died at Hastings
column5: Edric the Deacon was a landowner (thane) from Suffolk who joined Harold Godwinson in the Battle of Hastings and perished along with many others. Besides his ownership evident from Domesday book, which also indicates his death, not much else is known.

column3: Breme is possibly a title instead of real name
column5: Another landowner (thane) from Suffolk joined Harold Godwinson in the Battle of Hastings. Breme, along with Thurkill and Edric the Deacon, are one of many thanes who perished in the battle. The name, Breme, is possibly a moniker as its meaning is Renowned or Famous.

column3: Christian monk warrior
column5: Aelfwig was an abbot (head of a monastery) of New Minster during the Invasion of England. Believed to be a brother of Earl Godwine of Wessex and therefore, uncle of Harold Godwinson. He and twelve fellow monks joined Harold's force in the Battle of Hastings. Equipped with monk robes and chainmail, they are no doubt one of the literal warrior monks often seen in fictional stories. Aelfwig was, unfortunately, one of the few named individuals that perished on Senlac Hill, likely along with his fellow monks.

column3: One of few known Saxon nobles that died at Hastings
column5: Aelfric was a landowner (thane) from Huntingdonshire who participated in  Battle of Hastings on the side of Harold Godwinson. He perished along with many others that day.

An unnamed warrior who was recorded to fight on the side of Harold Godwinson in the Battle of Hastings. He was believed to be a Huscarl of Gyrth Godwinson who managed to kill William of Normandy second horse in the battle with a javelin. He was then cut down by William himself who proceeded to rush into the Saxon rank with rage after two of his warhorses fell.

column3: Part of the last remaining Saxon rebels against Norman
column5: A Saxon noble of unknown early life, Morcar became the Earl of Northumbria with the assistance of the people and his younger brother Edwin of Mercia after they banished Tostig Godwinson. Morcar and Edwin were the ones who defended York when Tostig returned with the Norwegian army in the Battle of Fulford. After the defeat, the two joined forces with Harold and defeated the invader at the Battle of Stamford Bridge. Morcar attempted to elect Edgar the Ætheling as the king but failed. He then attempted several rebellions against William and finally surrendered. He became a prisoner for the rest of his life.

column3: Betrayed and killed during the rebellion against Norman
column5: The elder brother of Morcar of Northumbria, Edwin of Mercia and his brother were one of the most prominent Saxon nobles during Harold Godwinson's rule. Edwin was the key figure in the rise of Morcar to the earldom and helped his brother in various battles. He was also a leader of the Saxon noble's remnant that tried to rebel against William the Conqueror's rule. Edwin was betrayed and killed by his own retinues while travelling to Scotland to gather support.

column3: Military genius nicknamed Napoleon of Egypt
column5: Pharaoh Thutmose III of the New Kingdom was one of the greatest Pharoah in Ancient Egypt history. He expanded his empire into from Nubia to Syria in 20 successful military campaigns. The Battle of Megiddo against Canaan city-states was his first campaign. Excel in both government and military, his rule developed the New Kingdom into the world first superpower that no country could rival it.

column3: The first vassal to rebel against the young Thutmose III
column5: An Unnamed King of Kadesh who led the city-states rebellion against the New Kingdom shortly after Pharaoh Thutmose III ascend to the throne. He and the other leaders of nearby Canaanites nation and tribe probably wait for the right moment to start this rebellion since the reign of the previous Pharoah Hatshepsut. Personally led the army in the Plain of Megiddo but lost against the brilliant military mind of Napoleon of Ancient Egypt. He and his allies surrendered after the Siege of Megiddo and sent the sons as a hostage to Egypt.

An Unnamed Prince of Megiddo who participated in the rebellion against the New Kingdom along with other Canaanite city-states coalition. The prince took part in the Battle of Megiddo and fled from the field during the retreat. While his fate after the battle was not exactly recorded, it is reasonable to believe that Thutmose III might spare his life along with other rebellion leaders.

The king of Hungary, Croatia, and Bohemia. Louise (Lajos) II became a young king during the troubled time of the Ottoman Empire's supremacy over Eastern Europe. He led Hungary against the Ottoman by refusing to pay tribute after his ascension, hoping that the other Christian nations would support his country in times of crisis. Such hope was displaced when the Ottoman Empire under Suleiman invaded Hungary in 1526 AD. Louise personally led the army and fought in the Battle of Mohács, where he was shot and died while retreating from the battle at the age of 20 years old.

A Hungarian Catholic monk and archbishop. A competent military commander who fought in numerous battles, including ones against the Ottoman Empire. Pál Tomori was commonly considered the hero of Hungary, even in modern times. For his talent and renown, Louise II elected Pál as the commander-in-chief of the Hungarian royal army during the Battle of Mohács. Pál personally led the first charge on the unprepared Ottoman army when the battle started. He died while rallying the retreating knights when the tide of the battle turned.

column3: Disappeared completely after the Battle of Mohács
column5: A high-ranking Hungarian noble and a younger brother of King John I of Hungary (who ascent the throne after Louise II died in battle). He was chosen as the commander-in-chief along with Pál Tomori in place of his brother, who was absent from the battle. He fought in the Battle of Mohács but disappeared during the combat. Presumed dead, some believed that he assassinated Louise II during the retreat.

Previously a representative of the King (Palatine), Stephen VII Báthory or Báthory István was one of the most powerful nobles in the Kingdom of Hungary before its fall. He participated in the Battle of Mohács and survived the conflict. Fled to Slovakia with the former Hungarian Queen, he organised the last remaining Hungarian opposition with the support of the Holy Roman Empire's Emperor, Ferdinand I, whom Stephen elected as the next King of Hungary.

A Serbian peasant who claimed to be a descendant of old Serbian royalty. Jovan Cserni, "The Black", was one of the many Serbians who participated in the Battle of Mohács. Jovan survived the battle and fled to serve under King John I of Hungary as a cavalry sergeant. While fighting under the allegiance of the Ottoman Empire at first, he later started a rebellion against the Ottoman to create an independent Serbian state, which ultimately failed. His role in the rebellion made him the hero of the Serbian people.

Ferenc Perényi is the Bishop of Transylvania and the younger brother of Péter Perényi. He participated in the Battle of Mohács with three thousand troops after receiving an invitation from King Louise II. During the war council before the battle, he believed that the Hungarian army was no match for the Ottoman Empire's army in its current state. He and other nobles advised the King to postpone the battle and wait for reinforcement. With the petition denied, Ferenc fought and fell in the battle. His foster mother, Dorottya Kanizsai, and her servants were the ones who found and buried his corpse along with the other fallen.

Péter Perényi is the older brother of Ferenc Perényi and was the crown guard (Coroner) of Louise II. This man fought in the Battle of Mohács, but unlike his younger brother, survived the battle. Péter supported Emperor Ferdinand I of the Holy Roman Empire as the next King of Hungary and served as his crown guard. He repeatedly changed sides between King John I and Emperor Ferdinand I until Ferdinand suspected him of treason. Péter was then held captive in prison for the rest of his life.

Péter Korláthkői is the chief chamberlain of King Louise II of Hungary who participated in the Battle of Mohács and died in combat. Péter was gifted with a castle at Öreglak village from King Louise II. As he had no child, the castle was taken over by his wife and later on by the Bakith family.

The last Serbian Despot and the highest-ranking Serbian noble under the Kingdom of Hungary. Pavle Bakić fought against the Ottoman Empire throughout his whole life, including the Battle of Mohács. After the conquest of Hungary, Pavle joined King John I and fought against Ferdinand. After King John I lost in the Battle of Tarcal against Ferdinand, Pavle changed allegiance to the Holy Roman Empire as a captain of the Serbian contingent. He participated in the Holy Roman Empire's campaign against the Ottoman Empire and died at the Battle of Gorjani.

The second last Despot of Serbia, Radics Bosics, was among the Serbian nobles during the rule of the Hungarian crown. He fled from Serbia during the Ottoman Invasion around 1500 AD to Hungary, similar to many other Serbian nobilities. Fought against the Ottoman Empire for his entire life, he participated in the Battle of Mohács and survived. He was revered and highly regarded by King John I of Hungary and was bestowed the title of Despot of Serbia (Stjepan Berislavić also held the same title bestowed by Ferdinand I). Radics died peacefully 1 year after becoming the Despot.

A tall, well-built and wealthy high-ranking Hungarian nobleman. Ferenc Batthyány was one of the rulers of Croatia during the reign of Louise II. He participated in the Battle of Mohács, bringing 3,000 infantries and 1,000 cavalries with him. He served as the commander of the right-wing flank. Fled from the defeat at Mohács, he was presented at the coronation of King John I of Hungary and served under him. After the fallout with Kristóf Frangepán, Ferenc went to serve Ferdinand I and fought against John I. Ferenc remained loyal to the Holy Roman Empire until he died of old age.

A noble, chief chamberlain, steward, general, and poet. Gáspár Ráskai was a man of many talents or maybe influence. He was a key figure in the resistance of Hungary against the Turk and later against the Holy Roman Empire. He participated in the Battle of Mohács as part of the King's guards along with Bálint Török and János Vitéz Kállai. He later became a vassal of King John I of Hungary and fought against the Holy Roman Empire in the subsequent civil war, including in the Siege of Buda in 1530 AD. At the end of his life, he published a historical book named, A beautiful story about the brave Francisco and his wife.

A Hungarian lord (Ban) of Belgrade. A member of an landowner patrician family that rose to become the most influential and wealthy Hungarian noble lineage in two generations through marriage, Bálint Török became a lord along with his father and brother at the mere age of 19. He became the commander of royal bodyguards for King Louise II in 1524 AD and participated in the Battle of Mohács. Bálint later became the vassal of John I of Hungary and the Ottoman Empire. His ambition and wealth attracted suspicion was imprisoned by the Sultan and remained in captivity at Istanbul until his death.

A commander of royal bodyguards of King Louise II, János Kállay of Nagykálló was likely a Hungarian noble of substantial standing. Not much is known about his life, except that he married the maternal aunt of Bálint Török and participated in the Battle of Mohács. He survived the battle, but not much of his life after is known.

László Szalkai, archbishop of Esztergom, was a lowborn from Zalká. His study at the parish school allowed him to learn Theology and the Latin language, which was beneficial to his career when he entered the royal court in 1494 AD. His career rose steadily from the Bishop of Vác to treasurer, chancellor, and archbishop. László fought in the Battle of Mohács and died in combat.

Fülöp Csulai Móré was a Bishop of Pécs. A savvy businessman and staunch supporter of the Hungary Kingdom against the Ottoman Empire. He often travelled around Europe to raise money for the war effort. He was appointed as a bishop in 1524 AD and died in the Battle of Mohács 2 years later, where he was wounded and bled to death.
Bishop Balázs Paksi of Győr was one of the commanders in the Hungarian royal army who participated in the Battle of Mohács and died. No other information of note is known about his life.
Ferencz Csáholi was the Bishop of Csanád. Another one of the Catholic church leaders who fought in the Battle of Mohács and fell in combat along with other commanders.
Bishop George Palina of Bosnia was another named leader of the Hungarian army in the Battle of Mohács. Fought valiantly until the end.

János Drágfi (Drágffy) was the state judge of the Kingdom of Hungary. A highly educated noble in the field of humanism, he already held a high-ranking title and was the master cupbearer of King Vladislaus II (Ulászló). He was part of the delegation to the Holy Roman Empire in 1522 to request assistance against the invading Ottoman Empire. János participated in the Battle of Mohács and served as a standard-bearer, and personally led 1,000 armoured knights. He was killed in the battle, and the flag was lost.

Ferenc Ország was the Hungarian chief court master under King Louise II of Hungary. A likely influential and high-ranking member of the court who administrate the royal palace. Not much is known about his life, only that he died in the Battle of Mohács against the Turks.

Péter Korlátkoi was the master of the doorkeepers for King Louise II of Hungary, along with János Pethő de Gerse and András Trepka. Péter and András both fought in the Battle of Mohács and died in combat. Péter served as the leader of Hungarian court troops. His body was found near the body of King Louise II, suggesting that they fought, fled, and fell together.

András Trepka was the master of the doorkeepers for King Louise II of Hungary, along with János Pethő de Gerse and Péter Korlátkoi. András and Péter both fought in the Battle of Mohács and died in combat. András  served as the leader of the Polish court troops.

Tamás II Szécsy of Felsőlendva, the chief lord of Vas, was another noble who was killed in the Battle of Mohács. It is unknown his accomplishment and activity, but we know that the Szécsy family was a long-time noble lineage since the 14th Century. However, Tamás's dynasty was in decline in his time, and the line ended with his children due to the lack of an heir.

The chief chamberlain from the Nyalábvár branch of Perényi house. Gábor (Gábriel) Perényi was the favourite of King Ulászló of Hungary. The king used to place Gábor under protection from other nobles' harassment and transferred the title of the Archbishop of Ugocsa from Bertalan Drágffy to Gábor. Often in financial trouble, either from debts or peasant revolts, he had to take out loans to support his estate and projects. He died in combat at the Battle of Mohács. Leaving his Croatian widow, Katalin Frangepán, to govern the estate.

Another dead noble among the fallen in the Battle of Mohács. Zsigmond of House Bánfy of Alsólendva, an influential noble house. Although his person is mostly unknown, it is likely that Zsigmond was one of the high-ranking court members.

A wealthy Palatine, János II Bánffy, was one of the nobles who participated in the Battle of Mohács. János was injured while his horse collapsed with him underneath, and his servant, Sándor Bakács, helped him. Both managed to escape from the Turkish pursuit with their life intact, and to commemorate this luck, János built a church in Lendván, Hungary. János became a supporter of János Szapolyai (John I) and acted as an ambassador to the Holy Roman Empire. He became a staunch supporter of the Church Reformation before his death.

A loyal servant of János II Bánffy, who also participated in the Battle of Mohács alongside his master. Sándor Bakács of Szentgyörgyvölgyi saw his master fall from his horse, teased him and dismounted from his horse to help before escorting him from the battle. For saving János, Sándor received a land property as a reward.
Ferenc Ernuszt (Hampó) Csáktornyai, royal chamberlain and baron of the Hungarian Kingdom. He fought in the Battle of Mohács and fell in battle.
A member of the Batthyányi family, János Batthyányi was another Hungarian noble who participated in the Battle of Mohács. He died in combat along with many others.

Schlick István is a Czech noble and vassal of King Louise II of Hungary who came to support the king in the Battle of Mohács and died in combat against the Turks, similar to other Czech and Moravian nobles.

Ferenc Balázsi (Balassa) is one of the Hungarian noblemen who fought and died in the Battle of Mohács. A Croatian lord from Transylvania and a captain of the royal infantry corp. Ferenc was indeed a powerful noble with a great connection to the Hungarian royal court since the rule of King Matthia.

The lord of Sáros and a chief chamberlain of King Louise II, and father of the infamous female warrior Anna Tarczay. Not much is known about the personal life of Miklós Tarczay, but that he fought and fell in the Battle of Mohács, leaving his family in turmoil amidst the conflict of grab for power between the German and Hungarian nobles.
Brother of Balázs Paksi of Gyor, János Paksy was also among the high-ranking Hungarian nobles who lost their lives in the Battle of Mohács.
Lord of Berzence and councillor of King Louise II. János Istvánfy was a member of the old Hungarian family and one of the many who died in the Battle of Mohács.
Imre Várady was a Hungarian noble of great wealth but no outstanding court title. He fought and died with his countrymen in the Battle of Mohács.

The captain of the royal infantry under King Louise II of Hungary, Mihály Podmaniczky is a member of an influential family from Upper Hungary. The arch nemesis of Rozson, another old Hungarian noble family, in which the two houses attacked each other for a decade. Mihály was often the leader in the conflict and led assaults on the Rozson's holdings. He participated in the Battle of Mohács along with his brother, István. Mihály was the one to die in combat, leaving his family in the care of his brother.

Bishop of Nyitra, István Podmaniczky is brother of Mihály Podmaniczky. The two both participated in the Battle of Mohács, but only István survived the ordeal. István was the only remaining high-ranking church official in Hungary, as most others perished in the battle. István was the one who crowned John I of Hungary a few months after the battle at Székesfehérvár. Then a year later, István changed sides and crowned Ferdinand I as the King of Hungary. When István died of old age, he had no heir himself, so Janos and Rafael Podmaniczky, sons of Mihály that István took care of after Mihály died, inherited everything.
Captain György Orlovsics of Zengi was one of the leaders of the Hungarian cavalry during the Battle of Mohács. He died in the battle.

István Aczél, lord of Bratislava and a trusted servant of King Louise II of Hungary, opposed the Turks in the Battle of Mohács. He escaped together with Louise when the battle was lost. Crossing the swamp north of the battle site, they both mysteriously drowned and died there.

Zsigmond Pogány of Csébi, lord of Máramaros, royal flag bearer and a member of the royal court, was the founder of the still-existing Maramaros branch of the Pogány House. He fought in the Battle of Mohács and died in combat.
János Tornally of Gömör, a minor noble of no notable history. He fought bravely and was killed in combat at the Battle of Mohács.
István Kállay, a mysterious noble from House Kállay with little to no record of his life remained. Possibly a close relative of János Kállay, both of whom fought and fell in the Battle of Mohács.
A noble of the Kingdom of Hungary, Miklós Forgács, fought in the Battle of Mohács and died in the process of combat.

A Polish knight, by order of Sigismund I the Old of Poland, came to support the Kingdom of Hungary against the invasion of the Ottoman Turks. Captain Lenart Gnoiński, with 1,500 men under him, consisting of Polish knights and infantries, met with the Hungarian army at Mohács. Together with the Hungarians, Lenart participated in the Battle of Mohács. It is unknown whether he survived the battle or not.

The famous Bishop of Vác, chancellor, and chronicler of the Battle of Mohács that he personally fought and survived. During his work as a bishop, István Brodarics often travelled to Poland and the Holy See as an ambassador requesting support against the encroaching Ottoman Empire. He was appointed as the chancellor by King Louise II and followed the King during the Battle of Mohács. He survived the disaster of a battle and sided with Ferdinand I in his bid for the Kingdom of Hungary. Not wanting to involve in the civil war, he fled to Poland for several years before returning as a peace negotiator for both sides.

Hannibal of Cyprus was one of the only few infantry leaders that survived the Battle of Mohács. Unlike other noble cavalries, the infantries could not retreat from the combat in time and were surrounded by the Turks, which led to the last stand during the last hour of the battle.
The head cellar master of the Kingdom of Hungary, Simon Horváth, accompanied King Louise II to the Battle of Mohács and became one of the Hungarian elites who died in combat.

The lord of Bratislava and Zala. Ambrus Sárkány attended the coronation of the Queen Borbála Szapolyai of Polish and acted as emissary for King Louise II to Ferdinand I for the matter of marriage alliance. He participated in the Battle of Mohács and was killed in combat.

The last remaining of the Pálóczi House, Antal Palóczi, was a noble of substantial influence in the Kingdom of Hungary. He fought and died in the Battle of Mohács. Although many nobles lost their lives in the fight, only the Pálóczi House went extinct from this battle.
Count of Czetrini, Mátyás Czetrini, was among the high-ranking Hungarian nobles who lost their lives amidst the fight in the Battle of Mohács.

Count Frangepán, not to be confused with the Croatian noble named Christoph Frangepán, who did not participate in the Battle of Mohács, fought and lost his life in the aforementioned battle. No other information is known about this mysterious man, but it is likely that this Frangepán was also of Croatian origin.

Gáspár Horváth of Vingárt served as the forager master for King Louise II of Hungary. He was appointed the horse master just a day prior before the Battle of Mohács as the previous one, György Báthory of Ecdes, was absent. During the battle, Gáspár stationed directly behind the king to prepare a fresh horse for offence and retreat. Despite the death of Louise II during the retreat, Gáspár, along with the two other horse masters, managed to escape unharmed.

One of the three horse masters for King Louise II during the Battle of Mohács, Ulrich Czettritz von Neuhaus was a royal court chamberlain from Bohemia and one of the eyewitnesses on the death of the King when he drowned while crossing the swamp brook. He was also among those who came back to retrieve the body of the king 50 days after the battle.

The lord of Szemere Village, Kelemen Szemere, was a minor Hungarian noble along with those from the Gagyi House. He accepted the call for arms by King Louise II and participated in the Battle of Mohács, where he fell in combat at the age of 64 years old.

column3: Greatest Sultan of Ottoman Empire

column5: An unnamed chieftain of the Sehagic family in Tesanj participated in the Battle of Mohács along with 20,000 other troops that travelled from there and joined Suleiman the Magnificent. The story is that he was killed in combat, and the banner belonging to a Bosnian unit was sent back to the chief's family as a reward. The flag still belongs and is kept inside the family home until today.
